name: A Brighter Future Child Development Center
A Kidz Place II, Inc.
detail:
Lois Hester, president of the company has a teaching degree with a BS in early childhood. She has been a public school teacher in both VA and SC. About 10 years ago she made a decision that would turn out to be one of the best in her life. Lois left the public school system and decided to apply all of her talents to preschool aged children, giving the children at our center the best possible foundation for success once they enter kindergarten. Our preschool program begins at 2 years old and continues until 4k. All of the lesson plans are overseen by Lois, she gives our other teachers pointers and tips to help them be the best at their job.
We have had several children come to us as infants and stay until they leave for kindergarten. This really gives us the pleasure of watching them grow and learn...at the same time it's hard to watch them go, spending that much time with a child is a blessing and it is easy to become attached :)
All of our employees have children of their own and I believe that gives them extra insight to preform their duties. We can relate to the parents and we take our jobs to heart. Having kids of our own, I feel helps us to take care of the other children the way we would want someone to treat our kids.

detail:
Thank you for visiting our site. Trinity Christian Academy exists to support families and churches in the work of making disciples.

We’re kind of fond of trees around here. One of the reasons is that they are one of God’s greatest metaphors for life. Trees are often symbolic of people in the scriptures. We have roots and branches; our lives grow from the past and branch out into the world around us. The Church too is like a tree, with roots and branches. One of our goals here at Trinity is to revive our awareness of our roots so that our branches produce the leaves for the healing of the nations (Ezekiel 47, Revelation 22:2).

name: Children's Place, Inc.
detail:
Our mission is to prevent the abuse and neglect of children in Aiken County. We believe that every child should live in a safe, nurturing, and healthy community. We achieve this goal through:

Prevention – We promote greater emphasis on primary and secondary prevention aimed at addressing critical family needs before children are maltreated. 

Collaboration – We believe all service providers should collaborate to mobilize community resources to insure that quality assistance is available to persons in need. 

Inclusiveness – We value the diversity among people and communities and will pursue our mission with inclusiveness and cultural competence. 

Flexibility – We are committed to being and organization that is flexible, open, and innovative while maintaining our mission and high professional standards. 

Strong Communities – We believe that support from strong communities is a critical ingredient in building and sustaining strong families, thus preventing child abuse and neglect.

name: Clover High School Early Childhood Program
detail:
Clover High School is a comprehensive high school that is dedicated to preparing all students to further their education in a four-year college, technical school or career path. The school offers a strong academic track that includes honors, advanced placement and distance learning curricula that prepare students to attend the four-year college of their choosing. 

The schools tech prep/career prep program provides courses with real world applications that prepare students for technical school or the workforce.  Auto mechanics, culinary arts, computer technology, building construction, agriculture, childcare, marketing, and business are some of the tech prep/career prep programs offered at CHS. 

CHS has an outstanding fine arts department that includes visual arts, theatre arts, and music.  The Clover High School Choraliers, Symphonic Band and Marching Band regularly compete with outstanding results at state competitions.  Their concerts are the "toast of the town." 

Equally outstanding are the school's extracurricular and interscholastic athletic programs.  Whether it is being judged the best Student Council in South Carolina, having an award winning AFROTC unit or winning an athletic championship, excellence is the standard.

name: Fleming/Felder Head Start
detail:
Head Start is a federal program that promotes the school readiness of children ages birth to 5 years of age from low-income families. This is accomplished by enhancing their cognitive, social, and emotional development.

Wateree Community Actions, Inc. operates three (3) sub-programs within its Head Start Program:

    Pre-School (Regular) Head Start Program - serves children 3 & 4 years of age, operates from August-May of each year, and has ten (10) sites located across Clarendon, Kershaw, Lee, and Sumter counties.
    Early Head Start Program - serves infants and toddlers, operates from August-June of each year, and has sites located across Clarendon, Kershaw, and Lee counties.
    Migrant Head Start Program - serves infants, toddlers, and pre-schoolers, operates from June-October of each year, and has two sites located in Clarendon and Florence (Lake City area) counties. Those whose children participate in the Migrant Head Start Program usually migrate from one area to another working in agiculture over a 12-24 month period.

name: Gail and Terry Richardson Center for the Child
Gateway Academy
detail:
Remember the last time you looked at something in wonderment? It was something so unique and interesting that it stopped you in your tracks. We aim to create those moments of wonderment each day in our school activities and curriculum. It is wonderment that makes a child associate learning with fun and leads to a successful approach to school as they grow up.

You’ll find an amazing group of teachers and caregivers at our preschools in North Carolina, South Carolina and Colorado.  Each day they focus on providing loving care and exciting learning activities for your little one.   In addition to teacher led lessons, self-direction is reflected in our classroom layout with distinct “discovery areas” offering children a wide variety of choices and play experiences. Each activity is matched to the characteristic ages and stages of ability for the age group, as well as the individual child.

We’re not only educators but we’re parents too. We know first-hand how much you want to stay connected with your child and what they are learning. Together, we chart a course for your child with an on-going dialogue to share ideas and progress. In short, you’ll be constantly informed about the development and progress of your child.

Keeping children safe during their day at Gateway Academy is of utmost importance. Our teachers establish guidelines in the classroom to involve children in a world of exploration, and for keeping them safe during that exploration.

We are proud to offer the kind of positive emotional support that builds self-esteem and helps assure success. Some of the most significant learning that takes place here is what children discover about themselves, self awareness that lasts a lifetime.

name: Georgetown Head Start
detail: Head Start is a federally-funded comprehensive child development program for 3 and 4 year old children. Besides the learning activities, the program ensures that children receive needed medical services, including age-appropriate screening and immunizations, dental check-ups, and nutrition and social services. A family service plan is developed to help improve the ability of the family to meet their needs. Parent involvement is a key element of Head Start.

name: Good Shepherd Day School
detail:
Established in 2000,

Good Shepherd Day School operates as a childcare facility with faith-based roots.  Good Shepherd Day School Ministry strives to offer affordable, high quality childcare for children of church members and community persons in a developmentally appropriate, stimulating and nurturing environment which fosters Christian faith.

Good Shepherd Lutheran Church believes in child care as a ministry.  The mission of our program is to provide care for children in a Christian environment conducive to meeting the children's needs for healthy physical, social, emotional, intellectual and spiritual development.  Our mission reflects Jesus' words in Matthew 19:14, "let the little children come to me, and do not stop them; for it is to such as these that the kingdom of Heaven belongs."

    Good Shepherd Day School provides care for infants through 5 year olds.
    We currently have a waiting list for all age groups.  Please call the Day School to be placed on the waiting list.  There is no fee to be placed on the waiting list. 
    We are open Monday through Friday from 7:30 am to 5:30 pm.  A late fee of $1.00 per minute will be charged for any child not picked up by 5:30 pm.  Fees will be doubled on the 3rd occurence.

name: Goodwill Head Start
detail:
Head Start is a federal program that promotes the school readiness of children ages birth to 5 years of age from low-income families. This is accomplished by enhancing their cognitive, social, and emotional development.

Wateree Community Actions, Inc. operates three (3) sub-programs within its Head Start Program:

    Pre-School (Regular) Head Start Program - serves children 3 & 4 years of age, operates from August-May of each year, and has ten (10) sites located across Clarendon, Kershaw, Lee, and Sumter counties.
    Early Head Start Program - serves infants and toddlers, operates from August-June of each year, and has sites located across Clarendon, Kershaw, and Lee counties.
    Migrant Head Start Program - serves infants, toddlers, and pre-schoolers, operates from June-October of each year, and has two sites located in Clarendon and Florence (Lake City area) counties. Those whose children participate in the Migrant Head Start Program usually migrate from one area to another working in agiculture over a 12-24 month period.

business hours: Our preschool hours are from 9:00 am - 12:00 noon. We offer extended care starting at 7:30 am each day and Lunch Bunch from 12:00 noon - 2:00 pm Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays. All of our classes are offered five days a week.

name: Greater New Hope Child Development Center
Greeleyville Elementary School
detail:
Greeleyville Elementary School was the first in our district to be recognized as a National Blue Ribbon School. In 2001 we added a First Steps Child Development class. In 2002 we were selected as a School of Promise Flagship winner by the SC Association of Administrators. We were among the first in the district to become a School-wide Title I school. Since 1998 Greeleyville Elementary has achieved deregulated status from the SDE, which allows the school to make site-based decisions.
 
We have been the recipient of numerous grants over the years, including a technology grant from Bridgestone Firestone, a 21st Century Learning Center Grant, the South Carolina READS Grant and numerous EIA Teacher Grants.
 
Most recently we were chosen to participate in the SC School Improvement Grant. We were one of only twelve schools selected in the state to participate in this project which incorporates behavior with reading achievement.
 
We have consistently met AYP. Our faculty is dedicated to making Greeleyville Elementary School a safe and positive learning environment.

name: Harvest Time Academy CDC
detail: We here at Harvest Time Academy believes that the first years of a child's life are critical to the development of a positive, self-confident, learner who will later go on to become a competent, happy, and a successful adult. Our primary goal is for children to feel safe and secure. We also believe that a clean, safe, nurturing, high quality, developmentally appropriate environment outside of the home is benefecial to the child. The needs of the whole child must be taken into account and these needs fall into the domain of cognitive, physical, emotional, and social. In addressing these areas along with helping to develop positive attitudes towards learning will ultimately enhance self-esteem and overall well being. Our primary goal is for children to feel safe, secure. Here at Harvest Time Academy we understand that children grow, develop, and learn at different rates, which is why our appropriate child to adult ratios allow for the meeting of each individual child's needs. All children are treated with the respect and kindness that they deserve.

name: Hawthorne Christian Academy (First Free Will Baptist Church)
detail:
Hawthorne Christian Academy is a non-profit, ministry of Chester First Free Will Baptist Church. The school is starting it's thirteenth year and begins caring for children as young as infants and continues this training through the 12th grade. The church and the school faculty and staff believe that we are operating an important mission, "reaching children and young adults for Christ". Our faculty and staff are professing Christians who are active members in their local churches.

We believe in academic excellence at HCA and have developed our teaching methods to create a learning environment where children can succeed. We accomplish this through not only traditional classroom instruction, but also utilizing various activities, hands on teaching, interactive technology, field trips, and small class sizes. In fact, our average student to teacher ratio is 10:1. Implementing these strategies along with quality, Christian curriculum gives HCA an academic advantage. Hawthorne uses the   A Beka Book curriculum in most subjects, and BJU Press in all mathematic courses. In addition, we test every student from K5-12th grade annually with the Stanford Achievement Test to ensure that students are achieving their potential. We have graduated thirty one high school students, and the education these graduates received has helped them succeed after Hawthorne in various public, private, and Christian colleges.

Hawthorne is continually growing, and in recent years we have added new playground equipment, opened a new library, upgraded our computer lab and network, developed an art lab, and created a science lab with modern chemistry, physics, and biology equipment. This past year we added "smart" classroom technology and presentation equipment to all of our elementary classrooms and in our middle and high school classes to give our students a visual way to understand complex concepts. HCA is a member of SCACS (South Carolina Association of Christian Schools) and AACS (American Association of Christian Schools), our preschool is DSS registered (DSS 905), and our cafeteria is DHEC inspected (A rating).

detail:
HOPE Academy exists to provide quality Christian education and childcare for your family. We are a nonprofit organization that values Biblical principles along with excellence in academics. Our goal is to partner with the families we serve to educate and disciple the children under our care. The values we hold as we fulfill our purpose are what set HOPE Academy apart from other providers in our area.


 My goal as Pastor of HOPE Baptist Church and Academy is to ensure that we represent the excellence of Jesus as we minister to your family. I grew up in a single parent home. I spent time in daycare and I was also a "latch key kid." I am thankful to this day for the support of local churches, and godly people who helped my mother to raise my siblings and I. Today I am an Officer in the US Coast Guard and the pastor of a great Church. I credit the care and education I received in those early years for any success I now enjoy. My passion is that your children will benefit from an even higher quality of care.


 Our academy could market itself in other formats to succeed in making money but this is not our focus. Our focus is to have the best teachers, curriculum and values to serve your children on behalf of Jesus Christ. God has blessed us in the past for this emphasis and I look forward to a strong future as we serve more and more families.

name: La Petite Academy
detail:
New friendships. New ideas. New ways to learn.

Welcome to the joys of childhood. Welcome to La Petite Academy.

What matters to us at La Petite Academy is simple: Your child. Here, exceptionally strong, sound social and educational foundations are formed. Here, children learn to respect one another. Learn together. Learn to work together. Learn to have fun constructively.

And discover how enjoyable learning can be.

It all starts by design. The free-flowing, open concept design of our facilities inspires a nurturing, interactive, and collaborative environment in which your child can thrive. Our schools and classrooms are designed to give children room to grow, room to share and room to be themselves. At La Petite Academy, open spaces and open concepts promote open minds.

In addition, our entire school is designed to ensure that your child’s safety and security remain our top priority. And communication is essential. With regular updates (including many photos) of your child’s experiences, you can feel comfortable that you are sharing this journey – every step of the way.

Spiritual Development
As your child develops mentally, physically, spiritually, socially and emotionally, we are committed to providing biblically based, age-appropriate experiences to allow each child to progress in these areas as his/her own level of ability while enjoying feelings of success.

Communication
We want your experience at Mon-Aetna CEC to be a friendly one.  Phones are available for parent/teacher communication if needed during the day.  Our open-door policy encourages parents to come by and visit their child anytime.  Parents receive frequent reports, explaining activities such as curriculum, meals times, nap times and each child’s continued progress.  Two Parent/Teacher conferences are scheduled annually for our 3 and 4 yr olds to mark progress and identify opportunities for improvements.  Weekly lesson plans, monthly newsletters and our Facebook page (Mon-Aetna CEC) also keep everyone up to date. 

Accredited Program
We choose to offer the BEST!  Since 2003, Mon-Aetna CEC is Union's only 'quality care' program in the state-run Advocates for Better Childcare (ABC).  This means better trained teachers, better learning environments and better quality care for your child.  The CEC is also in compliance as a licensed facility through DSS and the State Fire Marshall, and Level III (Exemplary) on the SC Church Weekday Education Evaluation Guide.

Our Infants through Two yr. olds Classrooms follow guidelines set forth by the South Carolina Program for Infant/Toddler Care (SCPITC) and we are Union's only Child Development Education Pilot Program (CDEPP) center, offering free full-day 4 yr. old kindergarten to qualifying participants.  

Safety and Security
From our buses to the classrooms, we provide ultimate child safety and security.  Staff are easily identified by their staff uniforms and photo ID’s.  Entry to the facility requires a proxy card and cameras monitor all classrooms and entrances.  Background checks are performed on all staff and volunteers.

Age Appropriate Classrooms
Your child can grow with other children who are at the same developmental stage.  Separating children by advancing milestones allows for a safer and more organized, efficient classroom and, thus, a better learning environment.  This is done primarily through hands-on activities in learning centers and positive Christ-like role modeling of our staff.  You’ll find our classrooms to be clean, orderly and comfortable for each child so he or she feels at home when he or she is at school.

Facility Advantages
Our new facility offers larger and brighter classrooms, easy access to an indoor play space, child size amenities and room to grow!

Highly Trained Teachers
Our 3 and 4K teachers have earned Associale or Baccalaureate degrees and our Infant, Toddler and Two's have earned their Early Childhood Credentials, qualifying them to be lead teachers in our facility.  Additionally, all are trained annually on blood borne pathogens to OSHA standards and many are certified in CPR and first aid.  All teachers log at least 15 continuing education hours annually-equipping them with up to date knowledge and information to best serve your child.

Grow Healthy Program
Mon-Aetna CEC was a pilot site for this now-implemented state program that provides guidelines for healthy living.  Through this program, children are offered meals and snacks that are low in fat and sugar and high in nutritional value.  Children are also educated on healthy lifestyle choices, given exercise guidance and allocated outdoor playtime each day.

The program relocated to its present location in late 1996 when the Family Life Center was completed.  Our center is a non-profit subsidiary of The Lutheran Church of the Redeemer.  Its purpose is to provide, in addition to child care services on a regular basis, an atmosphere in which children learn social and academic skills in a Christian learning environment in order to be successful in school.  The center is operated as a Christian ministry to members of the congregation and to the community at large and serves as a mission of the Church. We strive to maintain the standards set forth by the SC Department of Social Services, the SC Department of Health and Environmental Control, the State Fire Marshal, and the National Association for the Education of Young Children. Redeemer Children’s Center and Preschool is well-respected in the community as a provider of quality care with a strong early childhood curriculum. We are licensed to care for 331 children from ages 8 weeks to 5th grade afterschool. We have been providing quality child care to the Simpsonville area since 1982.

We offer a wide variety of services for our families including full-time care, preschool, afterschool pickup and summer camp. Full-day care services are available for ages 8 weeks to private K-5. We also offer preschool from 8:30-12:00pm for ages 3 and 4. Our afterschool program services 4 local elementary schools: Simpsonville, Plain, Bell's Crossing, and Bryson.

We pride ourselves here at FBSCEC in providing the highest quality of care. We are able to do so by limiting our class sizes as well as our teacher-child ratios. By succeeding in these two areas, we are also able to limit our rate of teacher turn-over. We strive to give our children the loving care and guidance they need to be successful in their formative years.

We are a Christian education program and we want the children to know that God loves them. Our Christian staff members teach the children about Jesus and the Bible. God gives parents and teachers the awesome responsibility of nurturing the children he has placed in our care. More and more, the need is growing for a place where children can receive care in a Christian environment by dedicated teachers while their parents are working. FBSCEC is privileged to be able to meet that need.

Welcoming students Pre-K through 6th Grade from all cultures, we are committed to respect for each person, celebrating our diversity. Along with a well-balanced curriculum, we offer age appropriate practices so children can experience success at school. After such positive experiences, we believe the child will develop a strong individual worth and a desire for continued learning. Meaningful play is the most effective form of instruction at the preschool age. At St. Paul UMC, we use a wide scope for activities to encourage a love for learning, emotional and social growth.

name: St. Paul's Day Care
detail: St. Paul’s Kindergarten and Daycare has served the Orangeburg community as a Christian daycare and learning development center since September of 1974, when the church officially integrated a private service that had existed in the church facilities since 1959 into its ministries. The daycare began as a service to the community with very few children. We are very proud to say that through the years it has grown into one of the largest daycares in Orangeburg with hours of operation from 7 AM to 6 PM Monday through Friday. We are also very proud of our reputation of excellence in child care and learning. The school has a 2K, 3K, and 4K nursery school and a kindergarten program with an average of 60 children in these programs. The school is licensed for 102 children with the Department of Social Services. Currently there is a total registration of 99 children including the after schoolers with a waiting list for some ages. Services provided by the school include an in-house speech therapist, a physical therapist, after school pickup, an after school program, and a very active summer program. The staff is certified with twenty hours yearly of training and all are certified in CPR and First Aid. We are very proud of the staff and administration and feel that we provide a stable, caring and loving “home away from home” environment for our children and their parents.

It is the key aim of our school to provide an environment and an educational program that encompasses the elements of moral, intellectual, physical, emotion and social development. As our moto is "Saints and Scholars", we aim to produce leaders in academics and servants in faith.

name: Stewart Heights Elementary School
detail:
Stewart Heights Elementary School opened its doors in November of 1962.  Initially it served students in grades one through six.  District reorganization necessitated changes in grade level locations and Stewart Heights began housing kindergarten through grade three.  In the school's fifty-one year history, four principals have been assigned to the school: Mr. A. W. Parker, Mr. Frank Lee, Mrs. Jayne C. Lee and Dr. Wendy Pace.  The facility has had two additions to the original structure. One new wing was opened in the fall of 1986 and the other was added in the fall of 1998.

Stewart Heights Elementary School maintains full accreditation from the South Carolina Department of Education and the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools.

The school is located at 1001 West Calhoun Street in Dillon, South Carolina.  Dillon is north of Florence, in the Pee Dee region of the state.

YWCA of Greenville-CDC
detail:
The YWCA is the oldest and largest multicultural women's organization in the world. Across the globe, we have more than 25 million members in 122 countries, including 2 million members in 300 local associations in the United States. More important than the numbers, is our mission to eliminate racism and empower women. We provide safe places for women and girls, build strong women leaders, and advocate for women's rights and civil rights in Congress.

Women come to us in times of crisis, as survivors of rape or domestic violence. They come for job training and career counseling. They come for childcare. They come for health and fitness. They come for a variety of reasons. But they come. And they leave with a renewed spirit, new skills, and stronger lives. YWCA associations are the bedrock of the organization. They are in almost every community nationwide, and their services range from Job Training, to Violence Prevention and Leadership Training. YWCA staffers, volunteers and friends are your neighbors, family members, co-workers and friends. To find out how you can help your community, contact your local YWCA at info@ywcagreenville.org.

detail:
P.R.I.D.E is our school's shared vision. P.R.I.D.E stands for Personalized, Rigorous, Innovative, Diverse, and Educational Environment. Students strive everyday to meet this vision. The students also have classroom leadership goals that they were responsible for creating.  

Our current scope of work is to create a student-centered culture and climate which involves student voice to create a classroom vision and Code of Cooperation. All students must be able to clearly articulate how these elements contribute to learning as well as evaluate themselves using the Code of Cooperation. As teachers and students collaboratively unpack standards, the students will be able to explain what they are learning, why they are learning it, and how they know when they've mastered it. By implementing Personal Mastery elements such as these, we are fostering a student-owned environment to support independent learners who are motivated to achieve.

name: Legacy Academy Woodruff Rd
detail:
With the choice of the name, Legacy Academy for Children ®, we laid the groundwork for the mission and philosophy of our organization. Your children are your legacy, hence our motto "the perfect beginning for your legacy". From the beginning, quality early care and education has been our focus. Our name and trade identity are synonymous with the highest end of the spectrum of educational facilities for children. We focus on those aspects which leave parents with a feeling of confidence and pride in the choice they make to enroll their children. Legacy Academy, Inc. monitors and assists each individual franchisee so that a consistent look and feel of a positive, nurturing, environment is felt and recognized when parents visit any or all of our schools. We require all of our new franchisees to submit for accreditation with NAEYC by their third anniversary. NAEYC stands for the National Association for the Education of Young Children. It is an independent body based in Washington, DC which is widely recognized as the foremost authority in early childhood care in the country. All schools are given help and guidance with this process along with encouragement to keep achieving the best possible environment for children.

Legacy Academy, Inc. has its own copyrighted curriculum, Framework for their Future ®. A team of early care and education experts created the curriculum specifically for Legacy Academy, Inc. and it is used in all of our schools. Each franchise is required to employ a curriculum coordinator who is on site at their school every day. The curriculum coordinator is there to monitor, instruct, and ensure that Framework for their Future ® is properly implemented and used in all classrooms. Monthly curriculum meetings are held at the corporate office to review all issues with curriculum.

In closing, choosing Legacy means choosing to make a positive difference in the lives of children.

name: Palmetto Christian Academy
detail:
Our purpose is to bring glory to God, specifically through the educational mission of the school. We glorify Him not only by the things we do, but also by the manner in which we do them; not only by the goals for which we strive, but also by the means we employ to reach them.

Palmetto Christian Academy of Greenwood is a non-denominational K3-12 college preparatory school.  We believe that God has given parents the primary responsibility for educating their children.  When parents choose to enroll their children in Palmetto Christian Academy, they do not abdicate that responsibility, but rather join with the school in obeying God’s command.  In 2007, a group of concerned parents recognized the need for a Christian school that understands and honors this relationship and is committed to academic excellence. Out of that concern, Palmetto Christian Academy was born.

Palmetto Christian Academy offers an environment in which students are nurtured in the Christian faith, challenged to grow in their understanding of the faith, and encouraged to take ownership of their relationship to God.  This is accomplished through classes in Bible and Christian thought and by teaching our students to look through the lens of Scripture in all subjects to determine what is true, that is, to develop a Christian worldview.  We understand the important role that modeling and mentoring has in the development of Christian character and lifestyle. All of our faculty and staff are chosen not just for their academic or technical expertise, but also for their ability to model their faith and share their lives with students.

Though there are many denominational differences, Palmetto Christian Academy embraces the common Christian belief that godly living must be in accordance with the Word of God and can only be accomplished through the power of the Holy Spirit. God’s calling upon our students involves more than a personal call to faith; it is also God’s call to our students to honor Him by becoming good citizens, responsible family members, and faithful members of His church. It is our desire to glorify God by enabling our students to respond faithfully to God’s call on their lives.

name: Coast to Coast Preschool
detail:
C2C Mission Statement:
“Safe and excellent childcare that makes a difference.”

How does C2C keep kids safe? We have 3 priorities at C2C.
One
First of all, we know that a parent’s greatest concern is the safety of their children. Our facilities, staff-to-child-ratio, background checks, procedures and training demonstrate our commitment to keeping your child safe while at C2C.

Two
Second, we want to be excellent in what we do – what does that mean? In child care it means creative programming, every minute of every day. At C2C you will not find an adult sitting in the corner with children running around in a chaotic environment. Our weekly themes drive our daily activities. Our motto, “Every week a new destination, every day a new adventure.”

Three
Finally, we want to make a difference. We are a Christian organization. We want to partner with parents to instill spiritual, emotional, academic and relational health in children.

We recognize the importance of a program that embraces diversity. An environment that celebrates differences can help children appreciate the richness of our world. Children need to learn how to interact with a variety of people, have respect for other cultures, and eradicate, through education, the culture of fear and intolerance.

name: Carolina Girls & Barefoot Boys Daycare Center
Williams Memorial Elementary
detail:
Williams Memorial, located in St. George, was started after the Civil War as an elementary school for African-American children. In 1922 the first principal of Williams Memorial was the Reverend S.D. Williams and the school included students in grades one through seven. By 1927 the school included grades one through seven and as education was rapidly changing, so was Williams Memorial. In 1942 the school held grades one through twelve and it was renamed Williams Memorial School in the memory of its first principal.
     In 1954 the current building was built on nine acres of land. Williams Memorial offered its students academics and extra-curricular activities. In 1970 the school was integrated and included grades four through nine. The faculty and staff worked tirelessly to give the students an education and life lessons that would help them through the ever-changing world.
     By 1993 the school was renovated and in 1994 it was renamed Williams Memorial Middle School and reorganized to include grades five through eight. Due to changing state regulations, the middle school was changed to accommodate grades six through eight and later the district reorganized the school, moving St. George Elementary into Williams Memorial Middle. This formed our current Williams Memorial Elementary School which serves Pre-K through fifth grades.

name: The Montessori School of Columbia
detail:
The Montessori School of Columbia began in 1983 when six families sought to give their children a challenging, enriching educational experience. Intrigued by the Montessori curriculum and its positive influence on their kindergarteners, these families established a Montessori elementary school for the Midlands. In 1999 the school expanded to offer a K3—K5 program.

At MSC we strive to develop the unique capabilities of each child. Guided by the work of Dr. Maria Montessori and informed by current research, our committed staff honors the natural curiosity of children. Our academically rigorous, self-paced curriculum allows children to work according to their own development levels.

In multi-age classes, children discover the dignity of work as well as the importance of caring for themselves and others. Since we attract families from a rich array of cultural and ethnic backgrounds, MSC students learn to be citizens of the world. Our mission is to foster a love of learning that will guide and sustain children throughout their lives.

name: South Sumter Head Start
detail:
Head Start is a federal program that promotes the school readiness of children ages birth to 5 years of age from low-income families. This is accomplished by enhancing their cognitive, social, and emotional development.

Wateree Community Actions, Inc. operates three (3) sub-programs within its Head Start Program:

    Pre-School (Regular) Head Start Program - serves children 3 & 4 years of age, operates from August-May of each year, and has ten (10) sites located across Clarendon, Kershaw, Lee, and Sumter counties.
    Early Head Start Program - serves infants and toddlers, operates from August-June of each year, and has sites located across Clarendon, Kershaw, and Lee counties.
    Migrant Head Start Program - serves infants, toddlers, and pre-schoolers, operates from June-October of each year, and has two sites located in Clarendon and Florence (Lake City area) counties. Those whose children participate in the Migrant Head Start Program usually migrate from one area to another working in agiculture over a 12-24 month period.

detail:
The Wonder Center is a day treatment program for medically fragile children. The center is staffed by Pediatric Nurses and a Child Development Specialist who provide extraordinary care and activities for the children.

Children may attend from ages 4 weeks until 6 years as long as their medical condition warrants the need for nursing care.  While many children of working parents attend the center, the program is also readily available for parents needing respite care, so that they may attend to other family needs.

The Wonder Center is part of the Children's Hospital and is under contract with the S.C. Dept. of Health & Human Services, which provides care for children through the Medicaid Medically Complex Children's Waiver. Anyone may recommend a child for admission, but orders from a primary care physician must be included for care to be provided. Please call for more information.

name: Charleston Center Happy Faces Busy Feet
Prince George Episcopal Church Preschool
detail: In March of 1995, the idea of Prince George Preschool was born. It was part of a renovation project for the church to provide more space for our growing congregation. The vestry also wanted to provide outreach to Georgetown families and thought that using our new building as a preschool would fill a growing need in the greater community. A committee was formed, plans were drawn up and construction began in 1995. The preschool opened its doors in September 1997 with 15 three and four year old children. A scholarship fund was started and continues today. Lee Jones was the first director and lead teacher. From this beginning we have continued to grow and expand our outreach to many more families in our community.  In the fall of 1998, we added a three-year-old class to our four-year-old class. Our enrollment jumped to 32 children. Sandy Gresham took over as director and Muff Boyd was hired to teach the three year old class. In 2004, Claire Jagger was hired as administrator and Lee Jones took the position of curriculum coordinator. In 2006, we added a three day a week preschool program for two year old class and the next year we expanded it to five days a week with before and aftercare. Tracy Morris was promoted to lead two-year-old teacher from her former position as after care aide. In 2007, we expanded the four-year-old program to twenty children. Our staff positions have grown from one teacher with aides to three lead preschool teachers with four assistants, one after care teacher with an aide, two after-school teachers, an administrator and curriculum coordinator. Today we serve over fifty children in the preschool. Many of our former preschool students participate in our after care program for elementary school children which serves around forty students. We also offer a summer program that is similar to our school program. We benefit daily from the support of the congregation and staff of Prince George and are inspired to create the best academic, emotional and spiritual learning environment.
